"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Ezra chapters 4–7
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-ezra-4-7.py

Ch4: Opposition to the building — the adversarial pattern that frames all covenant-building
     "We seek your God as you do" (4:2) — false brotherhood; Christ warns against false prophets
     Work stopped (4:24) — apparent defeat before divine intervention; third-day pattern
Ch5: Haggai and Zechariah prophesy; work resumes — prophetic renewal; Christ as the fulfillment of both prophets
     "Eye of God watched over the elders" (5:5) — divine oversight of the covenant community
Ch6: Darius confirms Cyrus's decree — pagan kings as YHWH's instruments; Isa 45:1 Cyrus-as-anointed
     Temple completed and dedicated — joy of completion; Christ's resurrection as ultimate temple-dedication
     Passover kept (6:19-22) — Christ as the true Passover lamb (1 Cor 5:7)
Ch7: Artaxerxes as "king of kings" (7:12) — the title Christ owns absolutely (Rev 19:16)
     Ezra's three-stage hermeneutic: study, do, teach (7:10) — the pattern of Christ's own ministry
     Hand of God on Ezra (7:6, 9, 28) — the providential-hand formula; Christ's hand never removed

mkt-christ requires an entry for every verse (91 total).
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

DATA = {
  "4": {
    "1": "<p>The adversaries of Judah and Benjamin heard that the returned exiles were building a temple to YHWH. The moment of covenant construction is immediately met with organized opposition — the Chronicler's pattern in which every act of building for YHWH draws resistance. Christ's own building project (Matt 16:18: 'I will build my church') is prefaced with the same promise of opposition from the opposite direction: 'the gates of hell shall not prevail against it.' The adversaries exist; the building proceeds.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'Let us build with you, for we seek your God as you do, and we have been sacrificing to him since the days of Esarhaddon king of Assyria.' The adversaries' offer — 'we worship the same God' — was a false claim of shared covenant identity. The syncretistic worship of the Samaritans (2 Kgs 17:24-41) combined YHWH-worship with other gods. Christ warns against exactly this pattern: 'Not everyone who says to me, Lord, Lord, will enter the kingdom of heaven' (Matt 7:21). Claimed shared allegiance does not constitute shared covenant standing.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Zerubbabel and Jeshua and the rest said: 'You have nothing to do with us in building a house to our God.' The refusal of contaminated partnership preserves the integrity of the building project. Christ's church is his building, and he is its builder — the question of who participates in the covenant community belongs to him: 'my sheep hear my voice, and I know them' (John 10:27). The clarity of covenant boundary protects the community from the dissolution that compromise would bring.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The people of the land discouraged the people of Judah and made them afraid to build. The external opposition moves from offer to intimidation — when false partnership fails, harassment begins. Paul describes the same escalation in Gal 4:29: 'as at that time he who was born according to the flesh persecuted him who was born according to the Spirit, so also it is now.' The pattern of covenant-opposition always escalates from persuasion to pressure to persecution.</p>",
    "5": "<p>They hired counselors against them to frustrate their purpose all the days of Cyrus king of Persia, even until the reign of Darius. The sustained nature of the opposition — not a single confrontation but a decades-long campaign through hired intermediaries. Christ himself faced sustained, organized opposition from 'the chief priests and the scribes' (Luke 19:47: 'they were seeking to destroy him'). The covenant community is not promised a conflict-free path but a path through conflict to completion.</p>",
    "6": "<p>In the reign of Ahasuerus, in the beginning of his reign, they wrote an accusation against the inhabitants of Judah and Jerusalem. The transition to a new king is immediately exploited to renew the accusation. The accusation pattern — legal filing against the covenant community — is the OT precedent for what Paul faces in the NT courts (Acts 24-26) and what the book of Revelation addresses: the accuser of the brothers (Rev 12:10). Christ is the one who silences the accuser permanently by his own blood.</p>",
    "7": "<p>In the days of Artaxerxes, Bishlam and Mithredath and Tabeel and the rest of their associates wrote to Artaxerxes. Another coalition of opponents, in a new reign, renewing the accusation. The names are Persian — the opposition now involves those embedded in the imperial administration. Christ's opponents similarly operate through the imperial judicial system (Pilate, the Roman governor) — the covenant community's opposition tends to instrumentalize the reigning political power.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Rehum the commander and Shimshai the scribe wrote a letter against Jerusalem to Artaxerxes the king. The specific named opponents — a commander and a scribe, administrative and literary power combined. The enemies of the building project bring both military authority and rhetorical skill to bear. Christ faced the same combination: Pilate (Roman military authority) and the scribes (religious literary authority) both contributed to the crucifixion.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The signatories of the letter — the judges, the governors, the officials, the Persians, the men of Erech, the Babylonians, the men of Susa. The multi-ethnic, multi-jurisdictional coalition against the building. The breadth of opposition against Jerusalem's restoration is the OT form of the breadth of opposition against Christ: Herod, Pilate, the Gentiles, and the peoples of Israel all 'gathered together' (Acts 4:27, citing Ps 2:1-2) against the Lord's anointed.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The great and noble Osnapper deported and settled in the cities of Samaria. The historical claim of prior ownership over the land — the adversaries are themselves deportees from the Assyrian period, arguing from historic settlement. Christ's opponents similarly argue from historic authority: 'Abraham is our father' (John 8:39), 'we have Moses' (John 9:28). Claimed historical precedent does not determine covenant standing.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The text of the letter: 'To Artaxerxes the king: Your servants, the men of the province Beyond the River...' The diplomatic letter form — the adversaries appeal to imperial authority using the official channels of the Achaemenid system. The church also faces the legal-institutional pressure of empire; Peter and Paul write letters to communities navigating exactly this pressure: 'Be subject to every human institution' (1 Pet 2:13), while also 'obeying God rather than men' (Acts 5:29).</p>",
    "12": "<p>'Be it known to the king that the Jews who came up from you to us have gone to Jerusalem.' The accusation framed in terms of imperial security — the returnees are presented as a threat to royal stability. Christ was similarly accused before Pilate in political terms: 'Everyone who makes himself a king opposes Caesar' (John 19:12). The political framing of covenant restoration as imperial threat is a recurring tactic.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'If this city is rebuilt and the walls finished, they will not pay tribute, custom, or toll, and the royal revenue will be impaired.' The argument from fiscal impact — the accusers calculate the economic threat. Covenant faithfulness is not a financial calculation, but the opponents make it one. Christ similarly faces the money-lenders in the temple (John 2:14-16) and the economic disruption of the Gerasene pig-owners (Mark 5:16-17): economic interests often align against covenant renewal.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'Now because we eat the salt of the palace and it is not fitting for us to witness the king's dishonor...' The loyalty-to-crown argument — the accusers present themselves as faithful imperial servants. The false loyalty that covers self-interest. Christ identifies this pattern in the Pharisees who 'honor me with their lips, but their heart is far from me' (Matt 15:8, citing Isa 29:13) — performed loyalty concealing covenant betrayal.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'A search may be made in the book of the records of your fathers. You will find in the book of the records and know that this city is a rebellious city, hurtful to kings and provinces...' The appeal to the historical record as evidence. The adversaries use the past to prevent the future. Christ's opponents similarly cite precedent: 'no prophet arises from Galilee' (John 7:52). But the covenant's future is not bound by the adversaries' reading of its past.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'We make known to the king that if this city is rebuilt and its walls finished, you will then have no possession in the province Beyond the River.' The threat of total imperial loss — the hyperbolic political claim. The scale of the claimed threat is disproportionate to the actual building project. Christ's opponents also escalate their claims to the catastrophic: 'if we let him go on like this, everyone will believe in him, and the Romans will come and take away both our place and our nation' (John 11:48). Fear of loss drives covenant-opposition.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The king sent his answer to Rehum and Shimshai. The letter goes up; the response comes down — the imperial communications system processing the accusation. God works through and around imperial correspondence: the same Artaxerxes who answers this letter will later commission Ezra (ch 7). The adversarial use of imperial channels does not exhaust imperial potential; YHWH can redirect the same channels for covenant purposes.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'The letter that you sent to us has been plainly read before me.' The imperial reception of the accusation — the process working as intended by the adversaries. Christ's own accusation was plainly read: 'The inscription of the charge against him read, The King of the Jews' (Mark 15:26). The public reading of the charge against the covenant community and its king is a recurring pattern that the resurrection overturns.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'And I commanded, and search was made, and it has been found that this city from of old has lifted itself up against kings, and that rebellion and sedition have been made in it.' The search of the records confirms the accusation — the historical evidence appears to support the opposition. Christ also appears condemned by the evidence: 'he stirred up the people, teaching throughout all Judea, from Galilee even to this place' (Luke 23:5). The apparent confirmation of guilt precedes the vindication.</p>",
    "20": "<p>'And mighty kings have been over Jerusalem, who ruled over the whole province Beyond the River, to whom tribute, custom, and toll were paid.' The historical grandeur of Jerusalem cited as evidence of potential for rebellion. The same grandeur testifies for Christ: his Davidic lineage and the greatness of Jerusalem's covenant history are the grounds for his messianic claim, not just the accusation's evidence.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'Make a decree that these men be made to cease, and that this city be not rebuilt, until a decree is made by me.' The stop-work order from imperial authority — the building halted by royal edict. Christ's mission was similarly halted by imperial authority (the arrest, trial, execution). But as the stop-work order in Ezra does not permanently end the building, the cross does not permanently end the mission: 'God raised him up' (Acts 2:24) — the decree of heaven overrules the decree of empire.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'Take care not to be slack in this matter. Why should damage grow to the hurt of the king?' The urgency in the royal command — the order given with a command to urgency. The adversaries' success feels complete. But urgency in the service of opposition to covenant renewal is always penultimate. The damage the king fears from the building project is nothing compared to the damage the enemy of covenant renewal ultimately suffers.</p>",
    "23": "<p>When the copy of King Artaxerxes's letter was read before Rehum and Shimshai, they went in haste to Jerusalem and by force and power made them cease. The opposition reaches its apparent peak: empire, force, and haste combine to stop the building. The resurrection of Christ is the answer to exactly this pattern: the stone rolled to the tomb, the guard set (Matt 27:66) — official power applied to ensure permanent cessation. It did not hold.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Then the work on the house of God that is in Jerusalem stopped, and it ceased until the second year of the reign of Darius king of Persia. The work ceases — not because the covenant failed but because the timing had not yet come. Christ's ministry also appears to cease at the cross. But the cessation is temporary; the prophets Haggai and Zechariah will restart the building in ch 5, just as the Spirit restarts the church at Pentecost after the apparent cessation of the cross.</p>"
  },
  "5": {
    "1": "<p>Haggai the prophet and Zechariah the prophet, a descendant of Iddo, prophesied to the Jews in Judah and Jerusalem, in the name of the God of Israel. Two prophets arise to break the building-cessation — the prophetic word as the catalyst for renewed covenant work. Christ is the fulfillment of both prophets: Haggai's promise of the 'latter glory' exceeding the former (Hag 2:9) and Zechariah's vision of the Branch (Zech 3:8; 6:12) both converge on him. Where two or three prophets speak in YHWH's name, Christ is the one to whom all prophecy points (1 Pet 1:10-12).</p>",
    "2": "<p>Zerubbabel and Jeshua rose up and began to rebuild the house of God in Jerusalem, and the prophets of God were with them, supporting them. The prophetic word energizes the covenantal leadership; the rebuilding resumes. Christ's resurrection similarly re-energizes the disciples who had scattered at the arrest: 'beginning from Jerusalem, you will be my witnesses' (Acts 1:8). The prophetic word and the empowering presence together restart the covenant project.</p>",
    "3": "<p>At the same time Tattenai the governor of Beyond the River and Shethar-bozenai and their associates came to them and said: 'Who gave you a decree to build this house and to finish this timber work?' The interrogation by imperial officials — a new round of opposition as the building resumes. Christ also faced repeated official challenges: 'By what authority are you doing these things, and who gave you this authority?' (Matt 21:23). The question of authorization is the recurring challenge to covenant building activity.</p>",
    "4": "<p>They also asked them this: 'What are the names of the men who are building this building?' The demand for names — the identification of the covenant builders for imperial record. Paul similarly gives his name to the authorities before whom he stands (Acts 22:3: 'I am a Jew, born in Tarsus'). The naming of covenant builders by imperial opposition is the precursor to the recording of their names in the Lamb's book of life (Rev 21:27).</p>",
    "5": "<p>But the eye of their God was on the elders of the Jews, and they did not stop them until the report should reach Darius and then an answer of letter be returned. The eye of God watching over the builders prevents immediate cessation — the work continues during the imperial investigation. 'The eyes of the LORD are in every place, keeping watch on the evil and the good' (Prov 15:3); for the covenant builder, divine oversight is protection, not surveillance. Christ's promise: 'I am with you always, to the end of the age' (Matt 28:20) — the watching eye becomes the accompanying presence.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The copy of the letter that Tattenai sent to Darius — the official report about the building being resumed. The imperial administrative machinery processing the renewal of the covenant project. Christ's ministry also generated official reports: Pilate wrote his assessment to the governor; the Sanhedrin's deliberations are recorded in John 11:47-53. The imperial record of covenant activity is itself a form of the testimony that will eventually reach all nations (Matt 24:14).</p>",
    "7": "<p>'To Darius the king, all peace.' The diplomatic opening of the letter. The covenant community's work is now officially in the communication stream of the Persian Empire. The church's witness eventually reaches the emperor himself through Paul (Acts 25:12: 'I appeal to Caesar'). The covenant testimony moves from local to imperial through the very opposition intended to suppress it.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'Be it known to the king that we went to the province of Judah, to the house of the great God.' The imperial officials' own language — 'the great God' — reflects the reputation of YHWH reaching the Gentile administration. The pagan witness to YHWH's greatness runs through the OT from Rahab to Cyrus to these administrators. Christ's mission is to bring this Gentile acknowledgment to its fullest form: 'every tongue confess that Jesus Christ is Lord, to the glory of God the Father' (Phil 2:11).</p>",
    "9": "<p>'We then asked those elders and spoke to them thus: Who gave you a decree to build this house and to finish this timber work?' The repeated question of authorization — each new official asks the same thing. The authorization for covenant building activity is always questioned by those who did not initiate it. Christ's authorization is from the Father: 'All authority in heaven and on earth has been given to me' (Matt 28:18) — the question of authorization finds its ultimate answer in the resurrection.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'We also asked them their names, for your information, that we might write down the names of the men at their head.' The imperial registry of the covenant community's leaders. The names of Zerubbabel and Jeshua are being entered into a Persian administrative record. Christ promises a different registry: 'I will confess his name before my Father and before his angels' (Rev 3:5) — the names of the faithful entered into the eternal record that no imperial edict can expunge.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'And this was their reply to us: We are the servants of the God of heaven and earth, and we are rebuilding the house that was built many years ago, which a great king of Israel built and finished.' The builders' self-identification: servants of the God of heaven and earth. The claim goes beyond local religious identity to cosmic authority — the God of heaven and earth built the institution that heaven's servants are now rebuilding. Christ's mission rests on the same cosmic authorization: 'my Father is working until now, and I am working' (John 5:17).</p>",
    "12": "<p>'But because our fathers had angered the God of heaven, he gave them into the hand of Nebuchadnezzar the king of Babylon, the Chaldean, who destroyed this house and carried away the people to Babylonia.' The builders' honest confession of why the house was destroyed — covenant faithlessness, divine judgment, exile. The same explanatory honesty governs the NT's account of Israel's history (Acts 7:51-53). Christ does not paper over the history of covenant failure; he enters into it to resolve it.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'However, in the first year of Cyrus king of Babylon, Cyrus the king made a decree that this house of God should be rebuilt.' The pivot: however, Cyrus. The counter-movement to the covenant judgment is initiated by a pagan king acting as YHWH's instrument. Isaiah had named Cyrus a century and a half before (Isa 44:28; 45:1) — the specific prophecy of the pagan ruler who would say 'let Jerusalem be built.' Christ is the fulfillment of the greater return: 'the year of the LORD's favor' (Isa 61:2, Luke 4:19) that Cyrus's decree anticipated.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The gold and silver vessels from the temple that Nebuchadnezzar had taken were handed over to Sheshbazzar the governor whom Cyrus had appointed. The return of the temple vessels is the tangible form of covenant restoration — the sacred objects removed in judgment are returned when the judgment is lifted. Christ's resurrection is the ultimate return of what was taken: 'you took him by lawless hands... but God raised him up, loosing the pangs of death, because it was not possible for him to be held by it' (Acts 2:23-24). What death took, resurrection returns.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'And he said to him, Take these vessels, go and put them in the temple that is in Jerusalem, and let the house of God be rebuilt on its site.' The restoration command — sacred objects returned to their proper place. Christ restores humanity to its proper place in covenant relationship: 'no longer strangers and aliens, but you are fellow citizens with the saints and members of the household of God' (Eph 2:19). The displaced made proper again, the vessels returned to the temple.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Then this Sheshbazzar came and laid the foundations of the house of God that is in Jerusalem, and from that time until now it has been in building, and it is not yet finished. The long duration between foundation-laying and completion — the building begun but not yet finished at the time of writing. The church is similarly in the same state: 'built on the foundation of the apostles and prophets, Christ Jesus himself being the cornerstone' (Eph 2:20) — the foundation laid, the building ongoing, completion awaiting the eschatological consummation.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'Now therefore, if it seems good to the king, let search be made in the royal archives there in Babylon, to see whether a decree was issued by Cyrus the king for the rebuilding of this house of God in Jerusalem.' The builders appeal to the existing decree — the prior authorization already on record. Christ appeals to the prior authorization of Scripture: 'these are my words that I spoke to you while I was still with you, that everything written about me in the Law of Moses and the Prophets and the Psalms must be fulfilled' (Luke 24:44). The covenant's authorization has always been on record.</p>"
  },
  "6": {
    "1": "<p>Then Darius the king made a decree, and search was made in Babylonia, in the house of the archives where documents were stored. The imperial archive search — looking for Cyrus's original decree. The record has been kept, though buried in the archives. The covenant's authorization is always recoverable because 'the grass withers, the flower fades, but the word of our God will stand forever' (Isa 40:8). What YHWH decreed through Cyrus remains in the record.</p>",
    "2": "<p>And in Ecbatana, the citadel that is in the province of Media, a scroll was found on which this was written: 'A record.' The scroll found in the archives of Ecbatana — the covenant's prior authorization surfaces from the Median capital. Christ's own authorization was found 'in the scroll of the book' (Heb 10:7, citing Ps 40:7): 'Behold, I have come to do your will, O God, as it is written of me.' The record was there all along; the search reveals it.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'In the first year of Cyrus the king, Cyrus the king issued a decree: Concerning the house of God at Jerusalem, let the house be rebuilt, the place where sacrifices are offered, and let its foundations be retained.' The original decree preserved — the first year of Cyrus, the specific authorization for the foundation and dimensions. Isaiah's prophecy named Cyrus specifically (Isa 44:28); the found scroll confirms the prophecy's fulfillment. Christ is similarly grounded in prior authorization: 'all the prophets bore witness' (Acts 10:43).</p>",
    "4": "<p>'Its height shall be sixty cubits and its breadth sixty cubits, with three layers of great stones and one layer of timber. Let the cost be paid from the royal treasury.' The specific dimensions and funding source — the empire paying for YHWH's house. The generosity of the imperial authorization is itself a covenant sign: 'the kings of the earth will bring their glory' into the new Jerusalem (Rev 21:24). The empire's resources serving covenant purposes is the OT anticipation of the eschatological ingathering.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'And also let the gold and silver vessels of the house of God, which Nebuchadnezzar took out of the temple that is in Jerusalem and brought to Babylon, be restored and brought back to the temple that is in Jerusalem.' The decree specifically orders the return of the temple vessels. The lost and the plundered will be returned — the covenant principle of restoration through justice. Christ's resurrection is the ultimate form of this return: what was taken by death (his life, his body) is restored by the Father's power.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'Now therefore, Tattenai, governor of Beyond the River, Shethar-bozenai, and your associates the governors who are in Beyond the River, keep away from there.' The adversaries commanded to step back — the very officials who opposed the building are now ordered by imperial edict to stand down. The reversal of power is total: the accusers become the commanded bystanders. Christ promises the same reversal: 'those who humble themselves will be exalted' and 'the stone that the builders rejected has become the cornerstone' (Matt 21:42).</p>",
    "7": "<p>'Let the work on this house of God alone. Let the governor of the Jews and the elders of the Jews rebuild this house of God on its site.' The imperial permission transformed into imperial command to leave the builders in peace. The freedom to build granted from the highest earthly authority. Christ's commission comes from the highest divine authority: 'All authority in heaven and on earth has been given to me. Go therefore...' (Matt 28:18-19) — the building commission backed by absolute authorization.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'Moreover, I make a decree regarding what you shall do for these elders of the Jews for the rebuilding of this house of God. The cost is to be paid to these men in full and without delay from the royal revenue, the tribute of Beyond the River.' Imperial funding for the temple — the adversarial administration now required to fund the building project it tried to stop. The resources of the empire redirected to covenant purposes. Christ's kingdom similarly draws on the world's resources for its mission: 'the wealth of the nations shall come to you' (Isa 60:5).</p>",
    "9": "<p>'And whatever is needed — bulls, rams, or sheep for burnt offerings to the God of heaven, wheat, salt, wine, or oil, as the priests at Jerusalem require — let that be given to them day by day without fail.' The empire providing the sacrificial materials — the daily provisions for temple worship funded from the imperial treasury. Christ provides the ultimate sacrificial supply: himself, once for all (Heb 10:10), so that no further daily provision for sacrifice is required. The temple economy dissolves into his single offering.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'That they may offer pleasing sacrifices to the God of heaven and pray for the life of the king and his sons.' The king requesting prayer from the restored temple — the empire acknowledging that YHWH's favor mediated through the temple is valuable. Paul commands prayer for kings and all in authority (1 Tim 2:1-2). The covenant community's prayer for political authorities is itself a form of covenant testimony to the one who holds all authority.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'Also I make a decree that if anyone alters this edict, a beam shall be pulled from his house, and he shall be impaled on it, and his house shall be made a dunghill.' The severe curse on anyone who reverses the building authorization. The severity of the protection mirrors the severity of the opposition — empire inverted from threat to shield. Christ's promise to his church is similarly absolute: 'on this rock I will build my church, and the gates of hell shall not prevail against it' (Matt 16:18).</p>",
    "12": "<p>'May the God who has caused his name to dwell there overthrow any king or people who shall put out a hand to alter this, or to destroy this house of God that is in Jerusalem. I Darius make this decree; let it be done with all diligence.' The pagan king invoking YHWH's protection of his own house — the Gentile ruler acknowledging the God whose dwelling place he is protecting. The nations' acknowledgment of YHWH reaches its eschatological form in Rev 21:24-26: 'the kings of the earth will bring their glory into it.'</p>",
    "13": "<p>Then, according to the word sent by Darius the king, Tattenai, the governor of Beyond the River, Shethar-bozenai, and their associates did with all diligence what Darius the king had ordered. The former adversaries now execute the king's commission with diligence — the complete reversal. The same officials who filed accusations against the builders now provision and protect the building. The reversal of the adversaries mirrors the cosmic reversal Christ achieves: 'having disarmed the rulers and authorities, he put them to open shame, by triumphing over them in him' (Col 2:15).</p>",
    "14": "<p>And the elders of the Jews built and prospered through the prophesying of Haggai the prophet and Zechariah the son of Iddo. They finished their building by decree of the God of Israel and by decree of Cyrus and Darius and Artaxerxes king of Persia. The building completed by the convergence of divine decree and imperial decree — YHWH's will executed through human authority. Christ's mission is similarly executed through the convergence of divine purpose and human agency: 'this Jesus, delivered up according to the definite plan and foreknowledge of God, you crucified and killed by the hands of lawless men' (Acts 2:23).</p>",
    "15": "<p>This house was finished on the third day of the month of Adar, in the sixth year of the reign of Darius the king. The third day — the temple completed on the third day of the month. The third-day completion is theologically resonant in the canonical narrative: Christ raises the true temple on the third day (John 2:19-21: 'Destroy this temple, and in three days I will raise it up'). The date is coincidental in the narrative; the pattern it embodies is not.</p>",
    "16": "<p>And the people of Israel, the priests and the Levites, and the rest of the returned exiles, celebrated the dedication of this house of God with joy. The great celebration of completion — the joy of the dedication after decades of struggle. The dedication of Solomon's temple was marked by the glory-cloud filling the house (2 Chr 7:1-3); this dedication is marked by joy of the returned exiles. Christ's resurrection is the ultimate dedication: 'the joy that was set before him' (Heb 12:2) is the eschatological joy behind which the dedication of the true temple stands.</p>",
    "17": "<p>They offered at the dedication of this house of God 100 bulls, 200 rams, 400 lambs, and as a sin offering for all Israel 12 male goats, according to the number of the tribes of Israel. The dedication offerings — generous but modest compared to Solomon's dedication (22,000 oxen, 120,000 sheep: 2 Chr 7:5). The diminished scale of the restoration mirrors the diminished glory Haggai describes (Hag 2:3); yet Haggai promises the latter glory will exceed the former. Christ is that latter glory — 'something greater than the temple is here' (Matt 12:6).</p>",
    "18": "<p>And they set the priests in their divisions and the Levites in their courses, for the service of God at Jerusalem, as it is written in the Book of Moses. The restoration of the organized worship-service — the Levitical divisions re-established according to the Torah. The church's organized ministry similarly traces to the appointment of the apostles, then deacons, then elders and overseers — ordered service in the covenant community as the pattern of worship-in-action.</p>",
    "19": "<p>On the fourteenth day of the first month, the returned exiles kept the Passover. The first Passover of the restoration period — the ultimate covenant meal of liberation re-enacted by those who have just experienced liberation from Babylon. Christ redefines the Passover at the Last Supper: 'This is my body given for you; do this in remembrance of me' (Luke 22:19). The Passover kept by the returned exiles anticipates the Passover kept by those returned from the exile of sin and death.</p>",
    "20": "<p>For the priests and the Levites had purified themselves together; all of them were clean. So they slaughtered the Passover lamb for all the returned exiles, for their brothers the priests, and for themselves. All pure — the restoration community keeping the Passover with uniform ritual purity. The NT Passover is kept with the purity that Christ provides: 'you are already clean because of the word that I have spoken to you' (John 15:3). The purity for the feast is now a gift, not an achievement.</p>",
    "21": "<p>It was eaten by the people of Israel who had returned from exile, and also by everyone who had joined them and separated himself from the uncleanness of the peoples of the land to worship the LORD, the God of Israel. The inclusion of those who separated themselves from the nations' uncleanness — converts who joined the covenant community. The widened Passover table: 'those from the nations' joining the feast. Christ's Last Supper is similarly eschatologically widened: 'many will come from east and west and recline at table with Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob in the kingdom of heaven' (Matt 8:11).</p>",
    "22": "<p>And they kept the Feast of Unleavened Bread seven days with joy, for the LORD had made them joyful and had turned the heart of the king of Assyria to them, so that he aided them in the work of the house of God, the God of Israel. YHWH turned the heart of the king — Darius of Persia called 'king of Assyria' because he now ruled the Assyrian territories. The divine sovereignty over royal hearts (Prov 21:1: 'The king's heart is a stream of water in the hand of the LORD') is the ground of the community's joy. Christ is Lord over all earthly authority: 'all authority in heaven and on earth has been given to me' (Matt 28:18).</p>"
  },
  "7": {
    "1": "<p>Now after this, in the reign of Artaxerxes king of Persia, Ezra the son of Seraiah... came up from Babylonia. After the temple's completion comes the arrival of the great scribe-priest. The 'after this' of ch 7 comes roughly 57 years after ch 6's events — a significant gap in the narrative. The covenant community's story does not end with the building; it continues with the equipping of those who will inhabit and teach the completed house. Christ similarly sends the Spirit after his own work of building is complete: 'when he ascended on high, he gave gifts to men' (Eph 4:8).</p>",
    "2": "<p>Son of Seraiah, son of Azariah, son of Hilkiah — Ezra's Aaronide genealogy. The legitimacy of Ezra's priestly authority is established through the lineage that traces directly to Aaron. Christ's priestly authority is established not through Levitical genealogy but through the divine oath: 'You are a priest forever after the order of Melchizedek' (Heb 7:17) — an order that transcends and supersedes the Aaronide line.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Son of Amariah, son of Azariah, son of Meraioth — the genealogy continues. The listing of priestly ancestors is the OT means of establishing priestly legitimacy and authority. Each name in the chain represents a generation of covenant fidelity in the priestly office. Christ's qualifications for priesthood come through a different chain: 'he became the source of eternal salvation to all who obey him' (Heb 5:9) through his learned obedience, not his ancestry.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Son of Zerahiah, son of Uzzi, son of Bukki — the genealogy continues tracing through the Aaronide line toward Aaron himself. The depth of the lineage (13 generations from Aaron to Ezra) demonstrates both the antiquity of the office and the continuity through exile. Christ's lineage in Matthew traces 42 generations to Abraham (Matt 1:17), demonstrating the full span of covenant history leading to him.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Son of Abishua, son of Phinehas, son of Eleazar, son of Aaron the chief priest — the genealogy reaches Aaron. The endpoint of the priestly genealogy is Aaron, the original high priest consecrated by Moses. Christ's priesthood reaches a different endpoint: Melchizedek, who preceded and blessed Abraham (Heb 7:1-4) — a priesthood more ancient than Aaron's and of a different, non-hereditary order.</p>",
    "6": "<p>This Ezra went up from Babylonia. He was a scribe skilled in the Law of Moses that the LORD, the God of Israel, had given, and the king granted him all that he asked, for the hand of the LORD his God was on him. Ezra's threefold characterization: skilled scribe, divine hand, royal grant. Christ fulfills the scribe-role in its highest form: 'And he taught them as one who had authority, and not as their scribes' (Matt 7:29). The 'hand of God' formula on Ezra reaches its ultimate expression in Christ: 'the Father who dwells in me does his works' (John 14:10).</p>",
    "7": "<p>Some of the people of Israel, and some of the priests and Levites, the singers and gatekeepers and temple servants, also went up to Jerusalem, in the seventh year of Artaxerxes the king. The second wave of return — each group of the covenant community's structure represented: priests, Levites, singers, gatekeepers, servants. The comprehensive inclusion of all temple-service roles in the return mirrors the NT's comprehensive gifting of the church: 'apostles, prophets, evangelists, shepherds and teachers' (Eph 4:11) — every role for the service of the house.</p>",
    "8": "<p>And Ezra came to Jerusalem in the fifth month, which was in the seventh year of the king. The arrival dated precisely — covenant history is historical, not mythological. The precision of biblical dating anchors the narrative in the real world. Christ's arrival is similarly dated: 'when the fullness of time had come, God sent forth his Son' (Gal 4:4) — the incarnation as historical event, not timeless myth.</p>",
    "9": "<p>For on the first day of the first month he began to go up from Babylonia, and on the first day of the fifth month he came to Jerusalem, for the good hand of his God was on him. The journey from the first day of the first month — the beginning of the journey coincides with the New Year, the first of Nisan, the month of Passover. The journey that begins at Passover and ends in Jerusalem is itself typologically laden. Christ's 'journey' to Jerusalem culminates at Passover too (John 2:13; 13:1).</p>",
    "10": "<p>For Ezra had set his heart to study the Law of the LORD, and to do it and to teach his statutes and rules in Israel. The three-stage hermeneutic: study, do, teach. The order is crucial — Ezra's teaching authority rests on his prior practice, which rests on his prior study. Christ himself embodies this order: 'he learned obedience through what he suffered' (Heb 5:8) before becoming 'the source of eternal salvation to all who obey him' (Heb 5:9). The teacher who has lived what he teaches is the model of Ezra fulfilled in Christ.</p>",
    "11": "<p>This is a copy of the letter that King Artaxerxes gave to Ezra the priest, the scribe, a man learned in matters of the commandments of the LORD and his statutes for Israel. The royal letter authorizing Ezra — the king describes him as 'a man learned in matters of the commandments of YHWH.' The Gentile king's description of Ezra honors exactly the quality that Ezra cultivated (v. 10). The world's recognition of covenant wisdom is itself a form of testimony — 'what wisdom is this given to him?' (Mark 6:2).</p>",
    "12": "<p>'Artaxerxes, king of kings, to Ezra the priest, the scribe of the Law of the God of heaven. Peace...' The king of kings title — Artaxerxes uses the Achaemenid imperial title. The title belongs ultimately to Christ: 'on his robe and on his thigh he has a name written, King of kings and Lord of lords' (Rev 19:16). Every earthly 'king of kings' is an anticipation and a shadow of the one who holds the title eternally and without competitor.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'I make a decree that anyone of the people of Israel or their priests or Levites in my kingdom who freely offers to go to Jerusalem may go with you.' The open invitation — anyone who freely offers may go. The voluntary nature of the return is emphasized: covenant restoration is not coerced but invited. Christ's call is similarly voluntary: 'If anyone would come after me...' (Matt 16:24). The kingdom gathers willing participants, not conscripted subjects.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'For you are sent by the king and his seven counselors to make inquiries about Judah and Jerusalem according to the Law of your God, which is in your hand.' Ezra sent with the Law in his hand — the covenant document as the instrument of assessment. Christ sends his disciples with the gospel: 'as the Father has sent me, even so I am sending you' (John 20:21). The missional sending is always accompanied by the authoritative word.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'And to carry the silver and gold that the king and his counselors have freely offered to the God of Israel, whose dwelling is in Jerusalem.' The freewill offering of the empire's silver and gold to YHWH — the Gentile monarch's spontaneous gift to the covenant community's God. The prophetic vision of the nations' wealth flowing to Zion (Isa 60:5-7) is being enacted through the imperial treasury. The church similarly receives gifts from unexpected sources as the mission advances.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'And all the silver and gold that you shall find in the whole province of Babylonia, and with the freewill offerings of the people and the priests, vowing willingly for the house of their God that is in Jerusalem.' The broader collection — both imperial gift and voluntary offering from within the exile community. The combination of imperial authorization and voluntary generosity mirrors the NT's funding of mission: Paul receives support from both the established churches and from individual donors.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'With this money, then, you shall with all diligence buy bulls, rams, and lambs, with their grain offerings and their drink offerings, and you shall offer them on the altar of the house of your God that is in Jerusalem.' The money designated for specific sacrificial use — not for personal enrichment but for worship. The principle of designated giving — money set apart for the house of God used for the house's purpose. The NT applies this to the collection for the Jerusalem saints (2 Cor 9:5-12): gifts designated for covenant community support are sacred trust.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'And whatever seems good to you and your brothers to do with the rest of the silver and gold, you may do, according to the will of your God.' The freedom given for the residual — Ezra's discretion within the covenant framework. Christian freedom operates within the same structure: 'everything is lawful for me, but not everything is helpful' (1 Cor 10:23). Covenant freedom is not license but the Spirit-guided use of latitude within divine purpose.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'The vessels that have been given you for the service of the house of your God, you shall deliver before the God of Jerusalem.' The sacred vessels entrusted to Ezra's care — the same vessels that Sheshbazzar returned (5:14-15) now being supplemented by new ones. The continuing replenishment of the covenant community's sacred equipment reflects the ongoing provision of Christ for his church: 'his divine power has granted to us all things that pertain to life and godliness' (2 Pet 1:3).</p>",
    "20": "<p>'And whatever else is required for the house of your God, which it falls to you to provide, you may provide it out of the king's treasury.' The open-ended provision — whatever else is needed, the imperial treasury will fund. The extravagance of the authorization mirrors the extravagance of divine provision: 'my God will supply every need of yours according to his riches in glory in Christ Jesus' (Phil 4:19). The treasury of heaven is behind the covenant community's mission.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'And I, Artaxerxes the king, make a decree to all the treasurers in the province Beyond the River: Whatever Ezra the priest, the scribe of the Law of the God of heaven, requires of you, let it be done with all diligence.' The decree going to the regional treasurers — the provision cascading through the administrative levels of the empire. Christ's authority similarly cascades: 'all authority in heaven and on earth has been given to me. Go therefore...' (Matt 28:18-19) — the delegated authority flowing from the source.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'Up to 100 talents of silver, 100 cors of wheat, 100 baths of wine, 100 baths of oil, and salt without prescribing how much.' The specific quantities with their ceilings — the empire's provision is generous but bounded. Christ's provision for his people exceeds bounded earthly provision: 'I came that they may have life and have it abundantly' (John 10:10). The imperial generosity, great as it is, is a shadow of the divine abundance.</p>",
    "23": "<p>'Whatever is decreed by the God of heaven, let it be done in full for the house of the God of heaven, lest his wrath be on the realm of the king and his sons.' The pagan king's awareness of divine consequences — fear of YHWH's wrath motivates imperial generosity. The fear of the Lord is the beginning of wisdom (Prov 9:10); even the pagan king operates within the framework of divine accountability. Christ is the one in whom 'the wrath of God against sin' (Rom 1:18) is fully addressed — on the cross — so that those in him face not wrath but the 'peace of God, which surpasses all understanding' (Phil 4:7).</p>",
    "24": "<p>'We also notify you that it shall not be lawful to impose tribute, custom, or toll on any of the priests, the Levites, the singers, the doorkeepers, the temple servants, or other servants of this house of God.' The exemption from taxation — the temple workers freed from imperial tribute. Paul similarly argues for the support of those who labor in gospel ministry: 'the Lord commanded that those who proclaim the gospel should get their living by the gospel' (1 Cor 9:14). Those devoted to the service of the house are not to be burdened by the empire's economic demands.</p>",
    "25": "<p>'And you, Ezra, according to the wisdom of your God that is in your hand, appoint magistrates and judges who may judge all the people in Beyond the River, all such as know the laws of your God. And those who do not know them, you shall teach.' Ezra given judicial and educational authority — the scribe as lawgiver and judge for the empire's Jewish population. Christ gives his disciples authority of a different kind: 'I will give you the keys of the kingdom of heaven, and whatever you bind on earth shall be bound in heaven' (Matt 16:19). The authority to interpret and apply the covenant is delegated to the covenant community.</p>",
    "26": "<p>'Whoever will not obey the law of your God and the law of the king, let judgment be executed on him with all diligence, whether death or banishment or confiscation of goods or imprisonment.' The judicial enforcement of the covenant law within the imperial framework — the secular authority enforcing religious obligation. Paul addresses the relationship between divine and human law (Rom 13:1-4): the governing authority as God's servant for good. The ultimate judgment, however, belongs to the one 'appointed by God to be judge of the living and the dead' (Acts 10:42).</p>",
    "27": "<p>Blessed be the LORD, the God of our fathers, who put such a thing as this into the heart of the king, to beautify the house of the LORD that is in Jerusalem. Ezra's doxology — the credit given immediately and entirely to YHWH who moved the king's heart. The same instinct governs Paul's doxologies throughout his letters: 'to him who is able to do far more abundantly than all that we ask or think... to him be glory in the church and in Christ Jesus throughout all generations' (Eph 3:20-21). Covenant success produces worship, not self-congratulation.</p>",
    "28": "<p>And who extended to me his steadfast love before the king and his counselors, and before all the king's mighty officers. I took courage, for the hand of the LORD my God was on me, and I gathered leading men from Israel to go up with me. The personal testimony: extended ḥesed, given courage, gathered companions. The hand-of-God formula closes Ezra's section as it opened it (v. 6). The narrative of divine provision bookended by the hand-of-God testimony. Christ's disciples are similarly gathered and sustained by the divine hand on their mission: 'you did not choose me, but I chose you and appointed you' (John 15:16).</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'ezra')
    merge_comm(c, DATA)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'ezra', c)
    count = sum(len(v) for v in DATA.values())
    print(f'ezra mkt-christ: wrote {count} verses across ch 4-7')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
